node.text:
Despite progress, a staggering 1 in 3 children globally is malnourished.

Growing poverty, climate change, conflict and the impacts of COVID-19 are all playing a role.

UNICEF and @WHO are working with governments and businesses to make sure every child grows up healthy and reaches their full potential.

node.title: Positive change for nutrition is possible

node.text:
Dancing, music and embroidery have kept 18-year-old Rasani going through Nepal's latest COVID-19 lockdown.

As children and young people continue to struggle with the impacts of COVID-19, UNICEF and partners are working to make sure the adults they rely on have access to vaccines.

Only together can we beat this pandemic. That's why wealthy countries must donate doses now.

#OnlyTogether #DonateDosesNow

When Swayam's entire family contracted COVID-19 in India, they had to make some serious changes.

node.text:
13-year-old Emtinan is working towards becoming a pediatrician or a gynecologist. But violence has cost her a precious year of school in Yemen. 

The chaos of conflict and COVID-19 has wreaked havoc on children's access to education. Over 2 million children have been displaced by war, and just as many are out of school.

UNICEF is helping provide safe places to learn, materials and teacher training — but more than anything, the children of Yemen need peace.

node.title: The cost of war in Yemen

node.text:
Youth are taking over the #Tokyo2020 Olympics! 

13-year-old skateboarders Momiji Nishiya (@momiji_nishiya830) from Japan and Rayssa Leal (@rayssalealsk8) from Brazil became gold and silver medalists, with 16-year-old Funa Nakayama (@funa_nakayama) from Japan winning the bronze. 

They are smashing gender stereotypes and making inspiring role models for young people around the world. Other young sportspeople are ready to leave their mark in the coming days. 

Who else are you rooting for? Share the inspiring young athletes you’ll be following in the comments!

Animation by @clintonnjunge for @voicesofyouth
#Skateboarding #Olympics2020

node.text:
“In the world of sports come gender norms. A lot of sports are always dominated by a certain gender, and when someone of the opposite gender decides to pursue it, they are called terrible names and are fitted into a typical stereotype. ⁣
⁣
Many women are sexualised and objectified by their looks rather than being admired by skill and strength. A lot are discriminated against and discouraged, from society and even their own coach. Likewise, when there are men who participate in more “feminine” sports such as dance and figure skating, they are stereotyped and bullied. Even the Olympics still ban men from partaking in rhythmic gymnastics and synchronised swimming competitions. ⁣
⁣
We shouldn’t let future generations hesitate to join a sport because of society’s preferences, but follow what they like and what they’re good at.⁣
⁣
I reimagine a world where girls and boys can equally enjoy sports according to their own likings without discrimination from other people.” Edriaa, 15, Malaysia. @voicesofyouth #Olympics

node.text:
Getting children back into classrooms is not enough. They need tailored and sustained support to help them readjust and catch up on their learning after COVID-19 school closures.

We are working with partners to support countries in reopening schools and recovering lost learning. The future of an entire generation is at stake. We need to get education back on track.

© UNICEF/UNI340679/Tesfaye

node.text:
Haiti didn't have a single COVID-19 vaccine before July. Thanks to a US donation of half a million doses, health workers and other priority groups are being vaccinated including Alabrie Marie, a neonatal nurse working at a hospital in Port-au-Prince. 

"Now that I got vaccinated I feel much safer to carry out my job and to protect children and their parents from COVID-19 infection."

To help health workers everywhere continue their lifesaving work for families, wealthy countries must #DonateDosesNow. Get involved by tapping the link in our bio.

© UNICEF/UN0493324/Fils Guillaume

Despite progress, a staggering 1 in 3 children globally is malnourished.

Growing poverty, climate change, conflict and the impacts of COVID-19 are all playing a role.

UNICEF and @WHO are working with governments and businesses to make sure every child grows up healthy and reaches their full potential.

Despite the proven and lifelong benefits of pre-primary education, around 175 million children worldwide are not enrolled.

Governments must invest in quality early childhood education and prioritize getting students back into classrooms.
